# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Brute Force : -

Create an answer matrix. Take every element from the matrix and place it in correct position in the answer matrix. 
Consider the 4*4 matrix filled with integers.
[0][0] -> [0][3]
[0][1] -> [1][3]
[0][2] -> [2][3]
[0][3] -> [3][3]
[1][0] -> [0][2]
[1][1] -> [1][2]
[1][2] -> [2][2]
[1][3] -> [3][2]
similary for other rows of the matrix.
The formula that comes out to be is placing i  to n - i - 1
Time Complexity : O( n * n) 
Space Complexity : O(n * n)

Optimized Approach :-
Observe Carefully, the first column of the matrix is actually the first row of the matrix but stored in the reverse order. Just transpose the matrix in order to get the desired matrix and then reverse it 
Elements of the diagonals stay as it is but the other element has to be placed

Time complexity:- O(n * n)
Space Complexity : O(1)

# Code
```
Brute Force :- 

class Solution {
public:
    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        int n = matrix.size();
        int m = matrix[0].size();
        vector<vector<int>> temp(n, vector<int>(m, 0));
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            for(int j = 0 ; j < n ; j++){
                temp[j][n - i - 1] = matrix[i][j];
            }
        }
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            for(int j = 0 ; j < m ; j++){
                matrix[i][j] = temp[i][j];
            }
        }
    }
};

Optimized approach :-
class Solution {
public:
    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        int n = matrix.size();
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n - 1 ; i++){
            for(int j = i + 1; j < n ; j++){
                swap(matrix[i][j] , matrix[j][i]);
            }
        }
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            reverse(matrix[i].begin() , matrix[i].end());
        }
    }
};
```

