solutions.content:
Entirely logic based solution. The idea is to divide matrix into several parts. 
First we deal with the outermost rows and columns. Then we start moving inwards, thus making the matrix shorter over every step.

We only deal with 2 rows and 2 columns at any given time. 

3 swaps are required for a 90\xBA turn. For example,
In a 3x3 matrix (0-indexed) :
matrix[0,0] <-> matrix[2,0]
matrix[2,0] <-> matrix[2,2]
matrix[2,2] <-> matrix[0,2]

Doing the above will turn the outer-most rows and columns in a 3x3 matrix by 90\xBA. The same logic can be generalised and applied for any **n x n** matrix.

For even number of columns, like 2x2, 4x4, 6x6, etc., the matrix can be easily segregated into parts containing 2 rows and 2 columns. For odd number of columns, the inner-most element need not be rotated, and hence, we are again left with a virtually even column matrix.

**swapNum** is defined only for fast swapping using pointers. You can do it with library swap function also.

**temp** is used to find parts of matrix. For example, in a 4x4 matrix, 
* first part contains :
	* rows -> 1 and 4 (all elements)
	* columns -> 1 and 4 (all elements)
* second part contains :
	* rows -> 2 and 3 (only elements of column 2 and 3)
	* columns -> 2 and 3 (only elements of rows 2 and 3)

Comment below if you have any doubts !!!

```
class Solution {
public:
    void swapNum(int* a, int* b){
        *a += *b;
        *b = *a - *b;
        *a -= *b;
    }

    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {

        int i = 0;
        int j = matrix.size() - 1;
        int k = 0;

        int count = 0;

        int temp = matrix.size()/2;

        while(temp--){
            for(int i = count; i < matrix.size()-1-count; i++){
                swapNum(&matrix[i][k], &matrix[j-k][i]);
                swapNum(&matrix[j-k][i], &matrix[j-i][j-k]);
                swapNum(&matrix[j-i][j-k], &matrix[k][j-i]);
            }
            count++;
            k++;
        }
    }
};
```

