The most voted solution ["A common method to rotate the image"](https://leetcode.com/problems/rotate-image/discuss/18872/A-common-method-to-rotate-the-image) is really wonderful, but it seems that many people don't know how it works. So I will show my view.

Briefly, the action **"first reverse up to down, then swap the symmetry"** is same to `matrix[j][n - 1 - i] = matrixOld[i][j]`, where n means the length of the matrix.

So you can even solve this problem like this (run in 4ms with C++):

```
void rotate(vector<vector<int> > & matrix) {
	vector<vector<int> > matrixOld = matrix; // To save the old matrix.
	int n = matrix.size();
	for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
	{
		for(int j = 0; j < n; j++)
		{
			matrix[j][n - 1 - i] = matrixOld[i][j];
		}
	}
}
```

Now let me show how I get this.

First we need to know that to rotate an image, we actually rotate each points of this image. 
For a given point **x(a, b)**. If we rotate it **θ** degrees around the coordinate origin **(0, 0)**, we get **x'(a', b')** where **a' = a * cosθ - b * sinθ** and **b' = a * sinθ + b * cosθ**. You can get this theory easily from [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_matrix). In this problem, **θ = -90 degrees** so **a' = b** and **b' = -a** **[1]**.

However, in this problem, the matrix does not rotate around the coordinate origin, but the point **((n - 1) / 2, (n - 1) / 2)** (index starts from 0). To deal with it, we merge two coordinates and set **offset = (n - 1) / 2** as the figure bellow shows. 

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/zeroonecode/image_1554810183.png)

For a given point in both coordinates, represented by **x(a, b)** and **x(i, j)**, we get **a = j - offset** and **b = -i + offset** **[2]**.

Substituting **a**, **b**, **a'**, **b'** in **[1]** by **[2]**, we get:
**j' - offset = -i + offset** and **-i' + offset = -(j - offset)** =>
**j' = 2 * offset - i** and **i' = j**

Since **offset = (n - 1) / 2**, substituting **offset** by **n**, we achieve **i' = j** and **j' = n - 1 - i**.

