solutions.content:
I was taught the merge sort top-down implementations, but not the bottom-up one. I found it was really more **intuitive, strightforward** than the top-down implementation...

---
**About Merge Sort**
Merge Sort is `devide and conquer` algorithm, it has 2 implementations:
1. Top-Down Implementation
2. Bottom-Up Implementation

Based on Wiki, 
> Merge sort is a divide and conquer algorithm that was invented by John von Neumann in 1945.[2] A detailed description and analysis of bottom-up merge sort appeared in a report by Goldstine and von Neumann as early as 1948.[3]

So bottom-up one is newer compared with top-down one seems like, and it has history. Interesting to learn...

**TP vs BU**
BTW, of course you can implement Top-Down here, but seems like few ppl do that.
Bottom-Up has few advantanges compared with Top-Down:
- Intuitive, easier to understand
- Iterative, no need to take recursion stack space

---
**Example Flow in diagram**
![image](https://github.com/ZhengguanLi/Leetcode-Notes/blob/main/148.%20Sort%20List%20-%20Screenshot%202022-02-26%20021549.png?raw=true)

---
**Code**
```java
class Solution {
    public ListNode sortList(ListNode head) {
        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(-1);
        dummy.next = head;

        // count the linkedlist size, since merge sort needs to split the list into
        // every 1 element, every 2 elements, every 4, every 8...
        int n = 0;
        // head can be safely overwritten, as we can already get head from dummy.next
        while(head != null) {
            head = head.next;
            n++;
        }

        // for the list, split to multiple sublists, i is size of the sublist starting from 1
        // and multiply by 2 everytime, 
        for(int i = 1; i <= n; i <<= 1) { 
            // merge sort, in each level, we merge from beginning
            ListNode pre = dummy;
            ListNode cur = dummy.next;

            // scan through the list once to split and merge sublist
            while(cur != null) {
                ListNode left = cur;
                ListNode leftEnd = split(left, i);
                // 1. if there is only left part, then there is no need to do the rest run
                // 2. avoid leftEnd.next NullPointerException
                if(leftEnd.next == null) break; 

                ListNode right = leftEnd.next;
                ListNode rightEnd = split(right, i);

                // back up for the next run
                cur = rightEnd.next;

                // cut down the connection for left and right
                leftEnd.next = null;
                rightEnd.next = null;

                pre = merge(pre, left, leftEnd, right, rightEnd);
                // connect with cur in case we do not have right sublist in the next loop, i.e.
                // "if(leftEnd.next == null) break;" above
                pre.next = cur; 
            }
        }

        return dummy.next;
    }

    // return the last node in the sublist. Note: I am not cutting down the tail of sublist now
    public ListNode split(ListNode node, int size) {
        size--;
        while(size-- > 0 && node != null) {
            if(node.next == null) return node;
            node = node.next;
        }

        return node;
    }

    // return the last node after merging, instead of head like we normally do
    public ListNode merge(ListNode pre, ListNode left, ListNode leftEnd, ListNode right, ListNode rightEnd) {
        while(left != null && right != null) {
            if(left.val < right.val) {
                pre.next = left;
                left = left.next;
            } else {
                pre.next = right;
                right = right.next;
            }
            pre = pre.next;
        }

        if(left != null) {
            pre.next = left;
            return leftEnd; // last node is leftEnd
        } else{
            pre.next = right;
            return rightEnd; // last node is rightEnd
        }
    } 
}
```

---
Time Complexity: `O(nLogn)`, Space Complexity: `O(1)` where `n` is the number of elements in the list.

