The two for loop is the commonly used format for bottom up binary reduction. For the list, we need to know the size of each merge part (len1, len2 in the code). The remaining code is the same as Merge Two Sorted List.

Simlified version for quick view:
```java
class Solution {
    public ListNode sortList(ListNode head) {
        int len = 0;
        ListNode curNode = head;
        //get the length of the list
        while(curNode!=null) {
            curNode = curNode.next;
            len++;
        }

        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
        dummy.next = head;

        // binary reduction
        for(int w=1;w<len;w*=2) {
            curNode = dummy;
            for(int i=0;i<len-w;i+=2*w) { // 0,2
                // head 1: i; head 2: i+w
                // each list length: 
                int len1 = Math.min(w,len-i);
                int len2 = Math.min(w,len-i-w);
                ListNode h1 = curNode.next;
                ListNode h2 = h1;

                for(int k=0; k<len1; k++) h2 = h2.next;     

                // merge two sorted list with len1 and len2
                /* code for merge two sorted list*/
                ...
                curNode.next = h2; // connect the end node with next section or null
            }

        }
        return dummy.next;

    }
}
